21737.title: Round Trip (A Space to Fall Back On)
21737.credit_line: Gift of the Alliance of the Indianapolis Museum of Art

extended_text.content:
Vito Acconci's career, which began in the late 1960s, has included Conceptual, Performance, and Body art, as well as installation, sculpture, and architecture. Round Trip (A Space to Fall Back On) belongs to a group of installations that Acconci produced between 1974 and 1979 that incorporates architectural elements, props, and audiovisual equipment.

For this work, Acconci devised what he calls a niche that is both "in the middle of (and, by its nature, somewhat apart from)" the gallery. Lightly stained wooden stools and boxes of various sizes spill across the two black walls, the floor, and the ceiling, suggesting items that we might see in a typical home. This hallucinatory, disorienting space is far from a conventional domestic scene, however. A vacant stool beckons the viewer to sit down across from a black podium that supports three spotlights and a speaker. The lights shine brightly into the area, blinding the viewer. The artist's voice and other unexpected sounds, such as a knocking, emanate from the podium, then move around the space, projecting from speakers hidden inside three boxes, before returning to the podium. This disconcerting work, which resists a coherent narrative interpretation, reveals the artist's powerful ability to force the museum visitor into an objectified role despite the artist's physical absence.

I want to put the viewer on shaky ground so he has to reconsider himself and his circumstances.
-Vito Acconci, 1981
extended_text.content_type: Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection (2005)
extended_text.title: Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection (2005)

extended_text.content:
Wooden stools and boxes spill across the floor, ceiling, and walls of this black corner, confounding traditional expectations of gravity. A viewer may sit on the solitary stool in this installation and feel disoriented by the arrangement of objects, lights cast from an adjacent podium, and sounds emitting from surrounding speakers. The artist's detached voice calls and responds to itself in a chaotic relay, loosely commanded by one "control point" speaker.

Since the 1960s, Vito Acconci's work with writing, performance, video, installation, and sculpture has explored the physical and psychological constraints of the human condition. Presently, the Acconci Studio architectural firm extends this consideration to the construction of public and private space. Round Trip exerts control over a viewer's sense of space by inserting unexpected color, sensory experiences, and laws of physics into the gallery.

35864.title: Portrait of Booth Tarkington
35864.credit_line: Gift of the Penrod Society and the Martha Delzell Memorial Fund

extended_text.content:
James Montgomery Flagg created this painting of Hoosier author Booth Tarkington in just one day-- August 19, 1916-- during a visit to Tarkington's summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine. Flagg was a renowned illustrator in addition to his activities as a portraitist. He created the famous "I Want You" image used as a recruitment poster in World War I.

Tarkington discussed the "zip-bang portrait" in a letter (transcribed below) to his friend Julian Street written the day after the portrait session. Tarkington was impressed with Flagg's lyrical use of color and his ability to capture Tarkington's spirit-- his "almost vicious mental energy"-- in such a brief sitting. Tarkington lightly pokes fun at "critic stuff" in the letter to Street, but his interest in art was deep. He was an art collector himself, and he was a trustee and supporter of the John Herron Art Institute, forerunner of the Indianapolis Museum of Art.

Tarkington and Street worked together with producer George C. Tyler from 1915 to 1917 on their co-authored play "The Country Cousin," which Tarkington discusses toward the end of the letter (where he refers to Tyler as "G.C.T."). Their play finally opened at the Gaiety Theater in New York in September 1917.

 

Booth Tarkingto's letter to Julian Street (from the Julian Street Papers, Princeton University Library)

Aug 20 ‘16

Dear Julian: –

Flagg came over yesterday and painted the most zip-bang portrait of a Nawthur—me. Darn ugly messy-faced chap sitting in great concentration at littered desk—summer clothes—author’s body slouching down inside ‘em—lazy body with almost vicious mental energy showing in the eyes. Homely as the feller is, the picture is beautiful—color managed so that a “lyric” (critic stuff) quality is there as much as if it were the portrait of some lovely woman.

It’s one of these things you stand before & say, “Holy Mike, but he has done it!”

Altogether Flagg’s too as distinctively as his house, his car and his nose. He beats the devil—here’s a one-day job that’s ready for any gallery—

Did G.C.T. send you new script? He seems altogether pleased—thinks plum right; peruse his note after reading & deduce. Be careful to read it as a thing played—The new type “Nancy” is to be just the least bit puzzling in earlier scenes with “George”—perhaps she affects her naïveté: She does, in fact.

N.B.T.
